			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/07/business/Datadesignjp/Datadesignjp-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/07/business/Datadesignjp/Datadesignjp-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/07/business/Datadesignjp/Datadesignjp-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002635747" width="592" height="354" alt="Climate Centralâs Surging Seas project highlights land lost to a rising ocean, not land that remains, a change of visual emphasis."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="354"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Climate Centralâs Surging Seas project highlights land lost to a rising ocean, not land that remains, a change of visual emphasis.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Stamen Design</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/01/06/a-makeover-for-maps/" data-title="A Makeover for Maps" data-description="Some graphic designers are trying to improve presentation of information using video and color rather than simple bar charts and graphs.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Like many designers, Eric Rodenbeck has had a long relationship with bar graphs and pie charts. He just thinks they are a little old school for todayâs data-filled world.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Rodenbeck has experimented with animation, three-dimensional maps that show the height of buildings by color changes and a representation of how photos spread on <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/facebook_inc/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Facebook, Inc.">Facebook</a> that looks like ice crystals forming on a car window. Heâs even tried to characterize in a graphic how people were communicating in back channels at business conferences, with the biggest talkers at the center of a series of circles.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He is, in short, trying to rethink how data is presented.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt doesnât work if itâs not moving,â said Mr. Rodenbeck, the head of Stamen Design, a San Francisco studio that <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/google_inc/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Google Inc">Google</a>, Facebook and <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/microsoft_corporation/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Microsoft Corporation">Microsoft</a> have all used for help in turning fast-paced digital information into easily understood images. âIt doesnât work if you canât touch it.â</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/07/business/DATADESIGN2/DATADESIGN2-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/07/business/DATADESIGN2/DATADESIGN2-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/07/business/DATADESIGN2/DATADESIGN2-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002635553" width="190" height="289" alt="Eric Rodenbeck, creative director at Stamen Designs, is rethinking charts."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="289"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Eric Rodenbeck, creative director at Stamen Designs, is rethinking charts.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Jessica Lifland for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nowadays, devices and people are unceasingly uploading all kinds of information about the economy, locations, weather and even what sweater makes them happy. With this flood of data, some believe traditional ways of displaying information do not work well anymore. So there is a demand for Mr. Rodenbeckâs sort of creative thinking about the humble pie chart.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Helping people easily make sense of that fire hose of information is a challenge. Better pictures (yes, designers believe pictures do often work better than a thousand words) can help. But many designers, particularly in the tech world, are straining for new ways to express information.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThere is no established visual language for this diversity of data sources and consumption,â said Tomoko Ichikawa, senior lecturer of design at the Illinois Institute of Technologyâs design school. âPeople are experimenting with a whole spectrum of things right now.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Rodenbeckâs comment about using more animation is more than an idea. Just as films are made by shooting 24 still images a second, then running them together to show movement, charts of fast-changing data reports can provide a clearer idea of the information gathered. The animated changes may be shapes on a map growing and shrinking, colors of bar charts changing or positions of lines rising or fading.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âYou canât generate a single design artifact for this much information,â he said. âYou have to generate a system that shows the flow.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A graphic that Stamen created for the Nasdaq index shows stock trading in increments as brief as a microsecond. Someone investigating the data can interact with the graphic, making it grow or shrink to see different patterns. Those simple changes can allow users to define what they see, to see changes that happen in a single minute, or even a single second, versus changes over a whole day.</p>
<div class="w480"><iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/31823489" width="480" height="378" frameborder="0" title="Untitled" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe><span class="caption">A visualization of financial transactions on the Nasdaq.</span></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The chart could be read one way by a pension fund manager interested in how the market digested the earnings within the overall dayâs trading. It could be read another way by a regulator investigating a spike in trading on the stock a few minutes before the earnings were officially released.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Douglas van der Molen, a former Google designer who created visualizations for ClearStory Data, sees the new graphics challenge as creating a way ordinary people can go on a data journey.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âYouâve got information moving at a high velocity and distributed teams with different skill sets looking at it at the same time,â he said. âGood visualizations arenât just about representing data well, but getting people to interact with it.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Within ClearStoryâs software is an inference engine that harmonizes the different ways data are recorded and figures out a common representation for all those categories. Mr. van der Molenâs software then picks a useful framework, like an unmarked map of the United States, where the data can be imposed. When new data is added, colors may become more intense, for example, or a particular state will pull away from the country as the information is presented.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe spent a lot of time thinking about how fast things should shift, what we call âperceived latency,â â Mr. van der Molen said. âIf things move too fast, or if the colors become too bright, it doesnât feel like a process they are controlling.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The more control people feel like they have over this stuff, he figures, the more likely they are to explore new features and better learn the system.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That giant tub of information is also consumed by people from diverse backgrounds. Theoretical researchers and repairmen both use <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/general_electric_company/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about General Electric Company">General Electric</a>âs electrical data. So how do you make it useful to both?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When the data shows something going wrong with, say, a wind turbine, âa Ph.D. looks at it as a sign of a system failure and wants to think about mistakes in his calculations,â said David Cronin, the director of interaction design at G.E.âs Big Data center in San Ramon, Calif. âA field engineer thinks about fixing something.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWeâre looking for ways to augment human perception to help in complex decision making,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Much like Mr. van der Molenâs ideas about data journeys, G.E. looks at what it calls âsemantic zooms,â so different meanings appearing as data is analyzed close up. This might mean initially looking at weather, electricity consumption and maps to figure out where a power outage is likely to occur. But close in on photos at street view it becomes clear that trees in a certain area should be trimmed so they do not fall on power lines.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Not everyone, though, thinks design needs changing, or at least that the way data is presented needs to be changed.</p>
<div class="w337"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/07/technology/07datadesign-tableau/07datadesign-tableau-hpMedium.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/07/technology/07datadesign-tableau/07datadesign-tableau-hpMedium.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/07/technology/07datadesign-tableau/07datadesign-tableau-hpMedium.jpg" id="100000002635483" width="337" height="253" alt="A visualization using Tableau of the routes taken by buses in London."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="253"><meta itemprop="width" content="337"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A visualization using Tableau of the routes taken by buses in London.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Tableau</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf I need to get somewhere, I still want a map,â said Christian Chabot, the co-founder and chief executive of Tableau Software, a data visualization company in Seattle. âIf I want to see things in time, I need a trend line. If I want to understand the magnitude of things, I want a bar chart.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Still, Tableau hires a number of psychologists schooled in human perception, as well as color specialists and designers to make sure its charts look as good as possible. Its revenue is expected to be up about eightfold since 2010, in part because of an innovative feature of its software that quickly turns numbers into visual representations. But Mr. Chabot does not see any relationship between his companyâs success and the huge increase in data consumption. .</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">No matter what the psychologists and specialists advise, there is just one caveat: âNo more than 18 colors at once,â Mr. Chabot said. âYou canât consume more than 18.â</p>
<footer class="story-footer">
